  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined as the process of making illegally obtained money appear legal by passing it through complex transactions or legitimate businesses. Key legal elements typically include:\n\n1. Basic legal components:\n- Concealing the source of illegally obtained funds\n- Transforming criminal proceeds into seemingly legitimate assets\n- Attempting to hide the origin of money gained through criminal activity\n\n2. Common legal jurisdictions recognize three primary stages:\n- Placement: Introducing illegal funds into financial systems\n- Layering: Obscuring the money's origin through complex transactions\n- Integration: Reintroducing funds into legitimate economic channels\n\n3. Typical criminal predicate offenses include:\n- Drug trafficking\n- Fraud\n- Corruption\n- Organized crime\n- Terrorism financing\n\n4. Legal requirements often involve:\n- Intentional conduct\n- Knowledge of funds' criminal origin\n- Deliberate attempt to disguise money's source\n\n5. Regulatory frameworks like:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (United States)\n- Proceeds of Crime Act (United Kingdom)\n- Anti-Money Laundering Directives (European Union)\n\nThese definitions can vary somewhat between jurisdictions, but generally share core conceptual elements about concealing illegal financial activities.",
